@title "In some cases, they are used interchangeably and in other cases they are used to denote behaviors of different complexity and duration. In the latter cases, the term “action” is usually referred to as simple ambulatory behavior executed by a single person and typically lasting for short durations of time. Examples of actions include bending, retrieving a cup from a cupboard, opening a door, putting a teabag into a cup, etc. On the other hand, the term “activities,” here, refers to complex behaviors consisting of a sequence of actions and/or interleaving or overlapping actions."
